CU AMIGA
--------

In response to the various "was there anything other than what is in the
press release" stuff -

I met with Petro Tyschtchenko this morning to discuss his plans and ask him how
the show had gone. He is following the GW2K party line on not making any rash
announcements - get used to it, this is the way real businesses are run, even
if it isn't the way certain tin toy companies we're used to hearing from work.

However Herr tyshctchstchstychetcetera was able to clarify a number of
issues and answered many of the points which have been of concern to the
Amiga community.
Expect a full write up of this in the next issue of CU, but a few choice
questions will be answered for the chosen of the CU-LIST

GW2k bought the Amiga to make money. They do not expect to make money now, they
see it as a long term development. This can only be a good sign. They do not
entirely understand the Amiga, and they recognise this. They do however realise
that the Amiga has a fiercely loyal userbase, and this is why they bought it.
GW2K's sales philosophy is to encourage user loyalty through good service, and
it was the amazing loyalty of the Amiga market that they want to buy into. They
do NOT expect us to start buying Amiga badged PCs.

GW2K also believe that the market is lead by enthuisiasts, and view the Amiga
as being the ultimate enthusiasts platform. GW2K reps at WOA were very
impressed at the general level of understanding about the platform Amiga users
have.

AI are selling off old stocks of A1200s and A4000s. These stocks are small,
and
AI do not intend to make more. AI will be concentrating on R&D, OS development
and supporting 3rd party developers before commiting to a next gen machine.
They
will not commit to a particular CPU until they have done more research.

AI will concentrate on licensing OS & technology to allow those more advanced
in research to provide true Amiga machines. PPC Amiga OS is a priority and
AI want to see PIOS 1 and A/box running genuine Amiga Workbenches.


My feelings about the buyout is that it is better news than we could have
expected. Petro is a happy man, and GW2K seem to be genuinely serious about the
Amiga. I hope this answers some of your worries, and check the July issue for
more depth and a bunch more info.

Comments, anyone?

Andrew Korn, CU AMIGA magazine

ATLANTA AMIGA 1997
------------------

Quick bits from the AAi meeting with special guest, Petro Tyschtschenko:

The Speech:

Sounded a lot like the one he gave at World of Amiga in London.  He would
give a few good points about GateWay2000, and then remind us of the fact
that Amiga International was a 'wholly owned subsidiary', so that we would
gain a sense that these good qualities would carry over to the Amiga 
business.  He kept inserting this line in his speech at different points.


The Q&A session:

Q: (Most asked question) How to get new users?
A: Show them the products, they'll see for themselves

Q: Distributors?
A: Keeping the same distributors, and expanding into new markets (i.e. 3rd
   world countries)

Q: Bundling a development environment with new computers?
A: Possibly.

Q: (My question) Adopt a strategy similar to Apple's in that Amiga Int. would
   release OS updates on a rigid schedule to keep user confidence high?
A: Not sure, but definitely wants to upgrade the OS and soon.

Q: Talking to Phase5 about supporting their PPC accelerators?
A: Many talks between Phase5 and Amiga Int, and even Phase5 and GateWay2000,
   no commitments though.

Q: How will marketing and advertising be handled by GateWay2000? 
A: All marketing will be done by Amiga Int, but might use the new advertising
   firm that GateWay2000 recently hired, again, no commitments.  GateWay2000
   will provide revenue for some operating expenses.  He was a bit vague on
   this point.

Q: Hardware and Software design schedule?
A: They need a new R&D manager before laying out a firm schedule.  A suitable
   candidate hasn't been found yet, though.  He did say that by this time next
   year, there would be new products and new users.

Q: Change the Amiga's name, and start with a clean slate?
A: No, the name has intellectual value.  Someone suggested a new Amiga model
   carrying the name 'Phoenix' because of the stuff the Amiga has been through
   and still comes back.

Q: Going to be at Comdex? 
A: Nope, gotta get back to Germany by Monday morning.  Two new hires to bring
   up to speed.

Q: What types of hardware updates do you envision?
A: Too specific, gotta wait for the new R&D guy to come in and analyze.

Q: Outsourcing hardware development?
A: Not entirely sure, but will definitely support 3rd party hardware
   developers, and will embrace industry standard components.

Q: Licensing?
A: Willing to license at all levels, hardware and OS.  Wanted to include a
   'Powered by Amiga' sticker on systems that use licensing though.

Q: Opening negotiations with Syquest, Iomega, etc, for including a high
   capacity disk storage in new amigas to take us beyond high density
   floppies?
A: Possible, GateWay2000 will deal with big companies for stuff like that.

Q: What got GateWay's attention?
A: They heard about the liquidation of Escom and new the value of the Amiga's
   patents.

Q: Why did they buy Amiga?
A: To not only get hold of the intellectual property, but also because of the
   large, very energetic user base community, and also, because they see it
   as a potentially very profitable company and product line.


He received a standing ovation when he was presented.  He's a likeable guy,
and very intelligent.  He's also level headed and practical.  One of the key
phrases he kept using was '...we shouldn't rush out a new product.  It takes
9 months to deliver a baby, and trying to deliver it early will only hurt the
child.  We don't want to hurt a new product by rushing it to market before it
is ready.' They went to dinner at some bar and grill later.  Petro went along
too.

There was also a guy there from the Jay Miner Society.  I was impressed with
his speech.  They are a group trying to keep the amiga community unified.
There was also a speech/demo from a guy from USRobotics about the new 56k
modems. Not bad either.



@endnode

